The paper deals with communication complexity and stream computation, which are core topics in theoretical computer science. The first contribution of the paper is new bounds on the information complexity of AUGMENTED-INDEX, which is a classic problem in communication complexity. This suggests that cs.CC (Computational Complexity) is a likely sub-category. The second contribution is about recognizing Dyck languages, which is a problem in formal language theory and can be seen as a streaming problem. This suggests that cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.FL (Formal Languages and Automata Theory) are likely sub-categories. The third contribution is about memory checking, which is a topic in verification and testing of computer systems. This suggests that cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) and cs.LG (Machine Learning) are likely sub-categories, as they both have connections to verification and testing.
